      <hedline>
        <hl1>Minor Injury on Major Stage</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By John Shaw</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Shaw, John</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>American hurdler Allen Johnson strains hamstring (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>An American athlete's minor injury was verbally probed and prodded for 30 minutes by reporters today, perhaps becoming, in the process, the world's most famous strained hamstring.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>An American athlete's minor injury was verbally probed and prodded for 30 minutes by reporters today, perhaps becoming, in the process, the world's most famous strained hamstring.</p>
        <p>But the man with the troubled left leg realizes that he is probably the least known of United States Olympic track title-holders.</p>
        <p>Allen Johnson, 22, won the 110-meter hurdles in the Atlanta Games in 1996 and, after winning this year's Olympic trials for the event in 12.97 seconds, is favored to gain gold again. If that hamstring holds up.</p>
        <p>John Shaw</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
